WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.320
Hello, welcome to my talk. Now we are going to talk about making apps that users love.

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:22.840
Not only that, because it's hard enough to make one app that users love, but what we

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:30.040
are trying to do is not only to do that for one team, but to help dozens of teams at the

00:00:30.040 --> 00:00:36.240
same time do it. So, this will be a story of some of the tools that we are using at

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:44.119
Appsilon to address this problem. But before we talk about what we do want to achieve,

00:00:44.119 --> 00:00:51.080
let's talk a little bit about what we want to avoid. So, welcome to the application graveyard.

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:58.799
This is a place where applications go where they are not quite what we set out to achieve.

00:00:58.799 --> 00:01:07.519
For example, some apps, strictly speaking, satisfy requirements, but perhaps no one ends

00:01:07.519 --> 00:01:15.000
up using them. Perhaps they are just too hard to use. Maybe they are too slow, they are

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:21.320
full of technical jargon, or have some other deficiencies that make them hard to use.

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:34.800
That can easily kill an app. And finally, maybe the app is just ugly. So, I'm not ashamed

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:43.959
to admit that from time to time, one of our apps can reach or get close to the application

00:01:43.959 --> 00:01:48.839
graveyard. Hopefully, it can be rescued from there. And I wonder, like, what's your experience?

00:01:48.839 --> 00:01:56.800
So, put your hand up if you have seen an app that was in the application graveyard. Yeah.

00:01:56.800 --> 00:02:01.720
A lot of you. So, hopefully, this talk can help you to avoid it in the future. So, that's

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:05.400
what we want to do. We want to escape the application graveyard.

00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:12.000
Okay. So, first of all, like, of course, we are going to try to do it through great design.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:17.399
But we don't only care about design for its own sake. Of course, we care about it because

00:02:17.399 --> 00:02:22.600
great design is a path to what we really want, which is adoption, people using our apps,

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:28.759
and impact. That their lives are better and the results of their companies are better

00:02:28.759 --> 00:02:32.880
as a result. And, of course, the opposite is also true.

00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:38.639
That if we ignore design, and we by accident end up with a bad design, this can be a significant

00:02:38.639 --> 00:02:42.800
obstacle to adoption and impact. So, that's what we would like to avoid.

00:02:43.839 --> 00:02:47.759
So, a few words about me. My name is Michał Parkowa. I'm a manager at Appsilon.

00:02:48.559 --> 00:02:54.160
And I manage our design team and the design tools, one of which I will tell you about in a second.

00:02:54.800 --> 00:03:01.839
And so, also, what I wanted to share is that in my career, I have learned two things that I

00:03:01.839 --> 00:03:06.160
wanted to share today. And that is that design is not only about how things look.

00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:12.960
And the second thing is that it's very hard to change a larger organization.

00:03:13.679 --> 00:03:19.039
So, hopefully, the tool I will show you in a second will help with both of those things.

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:27.839
But first of all, it's good to start with answering the question, what is great design?

00:03:27.839 --> 00:03:34.240
Because design is a very general word. Many people have different ideas about what it means exactly.

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:40.399
So, the first thing is to clarify what do we mean by great design in our context?

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:49.679
So, first of all, our assumption is that great design makes apps useful for a particular type

00:03:49.679 --> 00:03:54.320
of person, for a particular application solving an important problem for them

00:03:54.960 --> 00:04:01.279
in their particular context. So, number one trait or result of great design is usefulness.

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:08.080
Number two, that great design makes apps easy to use. So, it's not enough that it technically

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:14.800
solves some kind of problem. It helps if it's easy to use, if it doesn't provide or put

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:20.239
unnecessary obstacles in the path of the users. So, number two, easy to use. And number three,

00:04:20.239 --> 00:04:25.200
beautiful. So, as I said, it's not the most important thing. It's not the only thing

00:04:25.839 --> 00:04:28.880
when it comes to design. But, of course, it is one of the factors. And

00:04:29.440 --> 00:04:35.119
one reason is that there is a bias that beauty equals virtue. So, if it's beautiful,

00:04:35.119 --> 00:04:42.399
it gets judged better regardless. And, of course, we want our users to be happy about using the app

00:04:42.399 --> 00:04:48.079
and we want to be proud for the apps that we create. So, that's also a factor.

00:04:49.679 --> 00:04:56.000
Okay. And one thing I wanted to underline, those are some high level aspirations. But in practice,

00:04:56.559 --> 00:05:03.679
we are not expecting that everyone will hit perfection every time. So, it's enough to use

00:05:03.679 --> 00:05:09.279
the tool to make things better, to make the app a little more useful, a little easier to use,

00:05:09.279 --> 00:05:14.320
a little more beautiful. And that's already the start of a success. It doesn't have to be perfect

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:21.359
from the start. Okay. So, let me give you a quick example of how we use this framework

00:05:21.359 --> 00:05:26.880
in a recent project that we had. So, we built an app for Boston Medical Center.

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:32.640
It took about two months. It's called the Health Equity Explorer. It helps

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:39.839
doctors and researchers analyze data about population health to hopefully discover

00:05:40.399 --> 00:05:46.720
systematic factors that lead to good or bad health outcomes for a whole population or area.

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:54.320
And so, one thing we tried to put a lot of effort into making it useful. And we did it through,

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:58.320
like, close collaboration with the client. We talked almost every day to make sure that we

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:05.200
really understand their needs, that we understand their context, and that this app really fits

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:14.079
those things. And second, we tried to make it easy to use. And, of course, the key tool to make it

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:22.399
easy to use is user testing. So, as Maria told you a few minutes ago, it's about having the user

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:30.959
attempt to perform their task in the app without too much explanation, without being led by the

00:06:30.959 --> 00:06:37.279
hand. And then we can see, are they successful? Are they not? Where do they get stuck? And so on.

00:06:37.279 --> 00:06:42.720
And then we can go from there. So, we did a lot of user testing for this app. And then in the end,

00:06:42.720 --> 00:06:51.040
of course, we tried to add some spit and polish to make it a little nicer to look at. So, that was

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:59.600
a quick example of how a framework like that can be applied. So, the question is, like, okay. Great

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:05.600
design. Nice story. But so, who should be involved? Like, one thing, a great design. So, maybe the

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:11.440
designers are responsible for design. And, of course, designers should be involved. But it's

00:07:11.440 --> 00:07:16.239
not only designers. Like, other people need to be involved in the whole process to achieve that

00:07:16.239 --> 00:07:21.679
goal. Like, also managers, project leaders, engineers on the team, and maybe most importantly,

00:07:21.679 --> 00:07:26.959
the clients themselves. So, design is not only about beauty and design is also not only about

00:07:26.959 --> 00:07:34.720
designers. So, how do you make it happen? Well, now I'll show you. So, we have several tools that

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:41.679
help us do that. But today I'll show you one. And this one is our design planning and evaluation

00:07:41.679 --> 00:07:49.200
tool. It's a humble Google sheet with some sections. And so, now I will walk you through

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:53.920
the various sections. Don't worry about reading the details later. I will give you a link and

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:59.760
you can download it for yourself and learn more and hopefully adapt it or use it for your projects

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:05.679
as well. So, there are four sections. One is like a general information section, client up name,

00:08:05.679 --> 00:08:10.799
the history of our involvement. Because maybe we are taking over an app or maybe we build it from

00:08:10.799 --> 00:08:15.679
scratch or maybe we are evaluating an existing app that we didn't even make just to learn about

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:23.279
stuff. So, that's the first part. And then there are three parts relating to the three traits of

00:08:23.279 --> 00:08:29.519
great design. So, blue section, usefulness, green section, easy to use, red section, beautiful.

00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:38.159
So, zooming in on the usefulness section, one key thing is that we separate planning and

00:08:38.159 --> 00:08:45.119
evaluation. So, at first, we started with the evaluation part. But quickly found out that

00:08:45.119 --> 00:08:50.320
if we evaluate a project at the end, of course, that's too late to change anything about it. So,

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:58.880
definitely, we have to plan to achieve great design up front. And then that's at the end,

00:08:58.880 --> 00:09:04.479
the evaluation will be better. So, one thing, there's a section to just answer the question,

00:09:04.479 --> 00:09:10.320
like, who is it for? What is the target audience? What kind of users will use the app? Of course,

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:16.880
it's not enough to just say users. And what problem are we solving for them? And then we

00:09:16.880 --> 00:09:22.080
have sections for the things that we really want to achieve, which is adoption. How many people

00:09:22.719 --> 00:09:28.559
will be using the app? How often? Over what time? And what impact is it going to make? So, for

00:09:28.559 --> 00:09:35.280
adoption, it helps to ask up front, okay, how are we going to measure it? Like, just putting in the

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:41.119
instrumentation to measure adoption is already not obvious in some situations. So, how are we going

00:09:41.119 --> 00:09:48.000
to measure it? And then also, like, what would be a successful number? Like, what are we expecting

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:53.039
to achieve? And then, let's say, after a few months, let's say we have ten users. Is that a

00:09:53.039 --> 00:09:57.440
success or not success? Well, it depends on what kind of users, what problem they are solving.

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:03.200
Sometimes one user using the app once can be a success if it's like, I don't know, they show it

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:09.520
to some senator and they then pass some law based on the that they are convinced based on the app.

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:15.440
So, maybe that would be a success even though it's just one user. So, it's good to have those

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:22.320
conversations up front. And also, an important conversation that is good to have at the start

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:27.280
is that to imagine, like, okay, we've shipped the we are talking about some app. The client

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:31.679
maybe lists some functions that they expect in the app. But then it's important to ask, okay,

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:35.679
so let's imagine we ship the app. All the functions are there. And what will happen then?

00:10:36.239 --> 00:10:41.919
A very simple question. But it helps to uncover maybe gaps in our thinking that

00:10:43.919 --> 00:10:47.679
maybe to achieve the goal that they have in mind, maybe not all of those functionalities are

00:10:47.679 --> 00:10:52.239
necessary. Or maybe we need to do something extra. Maybe we need to do some training. Maybe we need

00:10:52.239 --> 00:10:57.200
to do a video explaining the app to people. Or maybe we just need to collect email addresses

00:10:57.200 --> 00:11:03.039
before we ship the app. There are many things in the general area of, let's say, product management

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:11.359
that we can do to achieve this bigger impact regardless of the shape of the app. So, that's

00:11:12.559 --> 00:11:16.880
this going through this section in the sheet helps teams to have those important conversations

00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:22.159
and to explain with clients, like, why are we asking those questions and in what context do

00:11:22.159 --> 00:11:32.000
we see it? So, that was the usefulness section. Ease of use section includes some various methods.

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:37.200
That's the general shape of the tool. In each section, we collect various methods that we are

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:42.000
experimenting with. And over time, we can have conversations. It's not mandatory to use all the

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:49.280
methods for all the projects. But it contains options to consider. So, for example, the main

00:11:49.280 --> 00:11:54.400
two things that we have in the ease of use section is, of course, user testing. So, that's the same

00:11:54.400 --> 00:12:00.960
thing that Mario was talking about with prototyping and quick prototyping showing users. And the most

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:07.280
important thing is that we don't want to explain it to users and ask what they think. We want to

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:13.840
see them use it with minimal explanation and then talk about it. So, that's the gold standard. User

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:20.400
testing for us. But, of course, there are also other ways. So, we like to use this list of 10

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:27.359
usability heuristics by Jakob Nielsen. That's an article that summarizes how to make apps that are

00:12:27.359 --> 00:12:34.159
easy to use. And so, for example, this is an example of a filled in evaluation for one of our

00:12:34.159 --> 00:12:40.159
apps with those Jakob Nielsen heuristics. So, as you can see, we did a good job on visibility of

00:12:40.159 --> 00:12:46.080
system status, but maybe not necessarily error prevention. So, that would be a signal to maybe

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:54.960
in the next iteration, we should think about error handling. And finally, the beauty part.

00:12:55.919 --> 00:13:02.239
So, of course, beauty is to some extent subjective, but the opinion of specific people is

00:13:02.239 --> 00:13:09.280
already a fact. So, we can work with that. We can have also expert feedback or also heuristic

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:13.520
evaluation using a slightly different set of heuristic evaluations just for aesthetics, not

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:21.520
usability. And finally, we had a good experience with an ebook called Refactoring UI, which contains

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:28.559
a lot of design tips that is specifically tailored for developers to use. So, if we don't

00:13:28.559 --> 00:13:33.520
have a professional designer involved, it helps to use Refactoring UI and go through

00:13:34.559 --> 00:13:39.919
just tips that are there. And you can get surprisingly far that way.

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:50.719
Yeah. So, those are our methods for making the app beautiful. And also, if you haven't seen

00:13:50.719 --> 00:13:57.200
Maria's talk, maybe you can catch it online later about the power of prototyping that also helps in

00:13:57.200 --> 00:14:06.719
this context. Okay. So, I showed you a lightning review of our this form that teams can fill in.

00:14:06.719 --> 00:14:12.559
But you might be asking yourself, but is anyone actually going to use it if we just send by email

00:14:12.559 --> 00:14:18.400
to all the teams, oh, here's a new form to fill. Please use it. That will probably not be effective.

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:24.159
And you'll probably be right that we are not expecting for people to just use it automatically.

00:14:24.159 --> 00:14:31.200
But we are treating this tool itself with the same framework that we propose for apps.

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:36.159
So, we try to understand the needs of the various teams of engineers, clients,

00:14:37.280 --> 00:14:44.479
leaders involved in those projects. We test it with users and improve. So, this sheet that you

00:14:44.479 --> 00:14:51.440
are seeing today is actually the third iteration. And hopefully, there will be more iterations after

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:58.880
that. So, and like we are using it also like talking about this tool. It's also a form of

00:14:58.880 --> 00:15:03.039
education. So, of course, we don't expect people to just understand and do everything perfectly

00:15:03.039 --> 00:15:13.599
themselves. Rather, we work with them like in a let's say interactive way. So, with that in mind,

00:15:13.599 --> 00:15:22.320
like we had in the past few months, we had nine practice applications of this approach. And here

00:15:22.320 --> 00:15:29.520
are some benefits that popped up again and again. So, one benefit is that this kind of approach

00:15:29.520 --> 00:15:36.640
helps us identify problems that can lead to bad user experience that we might otherwise miss. It

00:15:36.640 --> 00:15:42.159
helps you like zoom out, look at the broader context, but also go through in a systematic way

00:15:42.159 --> 00:15:47.760
through various things that even if you are an experienced developer, even if you are an

00:15:47.760 --> 00:15:51.599
experienced designer, you might not think about every time. So, it's like a checklist for that.

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:59.679
Second thing is it can help find low hanging fruit. So, sometimes like it takes the same

00:15:59.679 --> 00:16:06.880
effort to do it well compared to doing it poorly. If only we know what we should do. So, it can if

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:12.960
we do this evaluation early in the planning phase or evaluate an early prototype, we can

00:16:12.960 --> 00:16:16.400
find things that we can just automatically do better without additional investment.

00:16:17.520 --> 00:16:22.960
And number three, and maybe most importantly, it helps improve the quality of conversations that

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:29.280
we have around design within the team and with clients to create a shared understanding of what

00:16:29.280 --> 00:16:36.559
we mean by various things like great design, like usefulness, and so on. And it also helps people to

00:16:36.559 --> 00:16:44.080
just learn about the topic if they're interested in it. So, to summarize how to make apps users

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:51.039
love, well, first of all, think about more than just beauty. Number one, usefulness. Number two,

00:16:51.039 --> 00:16:58.880
usability. Making it easy to use. And finally, beautiful. And it helps to talk about it, to plan

00:16:58.880 --> 00:17:03.760
it, to be deliberate about this planning. And finally, to evaluate your progress so you can

00:17:03.760 --> 00:17:12.800
do it better next time. And most of all, just care about it. So, if you care about it, you can

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:20.079
download the slides from this QR code and this link, go.appsion.com. And you can talk to me at

